entry.title: Tweak GetOutermostWebContents usage in PrintIfAllowedByPolicy
entry.content:
The fix in crrev.com/c/4651379 works for LCAC as all URLs are sent for

scanning, but that might not be the case when cloud scanning uses this

code. When that happens, the WebContents used by

ContentAnalysisDelegate::IsEnabled also need to be the outermost one,

otherwise the URL comparison to check if a scan should happen might be

against the PDF reader's URL (aka chrome-extension://), or

any other embedded page.



This is fixed by simply moving the GetOutermostWebContents earlier in

PrintIfAllowedByPolicy instead of later in ScanAndPrint.

entry.title: [cc/tiles] Allow pre-paint tiles to be reclaimed when a client is idle
entry.content:
A tab can be both visible and not being interacted with at the same

time. A simple example would be a user with multiple browser windows. In

most cases, the foreground tab of each window is deemed visible. The

result is that we keep more resources than we probably should for such

visible-yet-inactive tabs.



In practice, on a macbook pro 14 inch, in the following scenario:

- Open a browser window with a single tab

- Scroll a bit

- Leave it alone



We are holding onto ~50MiB of invisible tiles as long as the tab is

visible, which could be days. For more details, see the linked bug.



This CL will reclaim the invisible tiles for the case where no frame has

been produced in the last 5 minutes. This is likely overly conservative,

since a tab with anything that animates (i.e. a GIF or an ad) will

prevent memory reclaiming, but it is a first, simple step.



This is gated by an off-by-default feature flag.

entry.title: [ios] Simplify WebStateListWillChange()
entry.content:
This CL simplifes the WebStateListWillChange() behavior.



Previously, 3 APIs were called in total when a WebState is detached and closed:

1. WebStateListWillChange() with kDetach and `is_closing=false` is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. WebStateListWillChange() with kDetach and `is_closing=true` is called.

4. and then a WebState is destroyed.



After this CL, 2 calls of WebStateListWillChange() are merged into one call. So 2 APIs are called in total when a WebState is detached and closed:

1. WebStateListWillChange() with kDetach and `is_closing=true` is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. and then a WebState is destroyed.



In this CL, the early returns, `if (detach_change.is_closing()) { return; }`, are removed because the operation for the detachment should be always executed when a WebState is closed.



This CL also fixes TabEventsMediator, which is affected by the above behavior change.

`[_ntpCoordinator stop]` should be called in `-stopNTPIfNeeded:` when there is no active new tab page.

Previously, `[_ntpCoordinator stop]` was called in the second call of WebStateListWillChange(). This CL, however, removed the second call of WebStateListWillChange().

The following events in TabEventsMediator are now executed when a WebState is detached and closed:

1. `-willChangeWebStateList:` is called and reset a tab.

2. A detached WebState is removed from WebStateList.

(https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:ios/chrome/browser/shared/model/web_state_list/web_state_list.mm;l=466;drc=b8143cf1dfd24842890fcd831c4f5d909bef4fc4)

3. `-didChangeWebStateList:` is called with `is_closing=true`.

4. `[_ntpCoordinator stop]` is called when there is no active new tab page.

entry.title: [ios] Replace webStateList:willDetachWebState:atIndex: and webStateList:willCloseWebState:atIndex:userAction: with willChangeWebStateList:change:selection:
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new WebStateListWillChange() API to notify a WebState will be changed to observers. WillDetachWebStateAt() and WillCloseWebStateAt() APIs are replaced by it.



This CL is a part of refactoring WebStateListObserver API:

Step 1 [Done]: Introduce WebStateListDidChange() and replace WebStateReplacedAt() with it

Step 2 [Done]: Replace WebStateInsertedAt() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 3 [Done]: Replace WebStateMoved() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 4 [Done]: Replace WebStateDetachedAt() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 5 [Now]: Introduce WebStateListWillChange() and Replace Will*() with it

Step 5-1: Introduce WillWebStateListChanged() and replace Will*() in the C++ side. (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4640748)

Step 5-2 [This CL]: Replace will*() in the Objective-C side.

Step 5-3: Simplify the API behavior. See the detail below. (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4650366)

Step 6: Migrate WebStateActivatedAt() and WebStatePinnedStateChanged() to WebStateListChanged()



The series of CLs in Step 5 will simplify the API behavior.

Currently, 3 APIs are called in total when a WebState is detached from WebStateList and destroyed:

1. WillDetachWebStateAt() is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. WillCloseWebStateAt() is called.

4. and then a WebState is destroyed.



After Step 5-3, 2 APIs will be called:

1. WebStateListWillChange() with kDetach is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. and then a WebState is destroyed.



See https://docs.google.com/document/d/1I1QUZAexM1eMI2l2oriZl5GARrtofNI0SxHUPB4h-YE/edit?usp=sharing for more details (internal document).

entry.title: [ios] Introduce WebStateListWillChange API
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new WebStateListWillChange() API to notify a WebState will be changed to observers. WillDetachWebStateAt() and WillCloseWebStateAt() APIs are replaced by it.



This CL is a part of refactoring WebStateListObserver API:

Step 1 [Done]: Introduce WebStateListDidChange() and replace WebStateReplacedAt() with it

Step 2 [Done]: Replace WebStateInsertedAt() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 3 [Done]: Replace WebStateMoved() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 4 [Done]: Replace WebStateDetachedAt() with WebStateListDidChange()

Step 5 [Now]: Introduce WebStateListWillChange() and Replace Will*() with it

Step 5-1: [This CL]: Introduce WillWebStateListChanged() and replace Will*() in the C++ side.

Step 5-2: Replace will*() in the Objective-C side. (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4650671)

Step 5-3: Simplify the API behavior. See the detail below. (https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4650366)

Step 6: Migrate WebStateActivatedAt() and WebStatePinnedStateChanged() to WebStateListChanged()



The series of CLs in Step 5 will simplify the API behavior.

Currently, 3 APIs are called in total when a WebState is detached from WebStateList and destroyed:

1. WillDetachWebStateAt() is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. WillCloseWebStateAt() is called.

4. and then a WebState is destroyed.



After Step 5-3, 2 APIs will be called:

1. WebStateListWillChange() with kDetach is called.

2. WebStateListDidChange() with kDetach is called.

3. and then a WebState is destroyed.



See https://docs.google.com/document/d/1I1QUZAexM1eMI2l2oriZl5GARrtofNI0SxHUPB4h-YE/edit?usp=sharing for more details (internal document).

entry.title: Reorganize data removal for media device salts
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, the global salt was deleted as part of global cookie

deletion. This CL creates a new data type for salts, makes it part of DOM storage, and deletes salts as part of deletion of browsing data.

The global salt is still deleted on global cookie deletion to preserve

existing behavior.



This is in preparation for a new asynchronous per-storage-key backend

for salts and its integration with the UI for deleting browsing data per

origin/storage key. That UI specifies DATA_TYPE_DOM_STORAGE as remove mask.

entry.title: Refactor transform updates for LayoutSVGContainer classes
entry.content:
Move the handling of the `needs_transform_update_` from the various

subclasses that support transforms to the base container class

(LayoutSVGContainer). This means that any side-effects on this flag

in the subclasses' CalculateLocalTransform() implementations can be

avoided.



This will help in supporting 'transform-box: stroke-box', since that box

can't be computed until after layout of any children has completed.



Bug: 924472
